  "evidence": "VERIFIED: 415 distinct *.unimelb.edu.au destination hosts exist in the CONTEXTUAL link graph alone — reproduced exactly via `tail -n+2 analysis/full-scrape/cross-site-flow.csv | cut -d, -f2 | grep 'unimelb.edu.au$' | grep -v ezp.lib | sort -u | wc -l` = 415, an order of magnitude beyond earlier reporting 'estate is really 20+ systems'. The sprawl is self-similar at every level and confirmed in the data: 8 Fine Arts cohort-year subdomains (art2021/2022/2023/2024/2025 + designproduction2022/2023/2024, all present as live hosts), one-team-one-subdomain research microsites (huntlab.science, tigrrlab.science, lecao-lab.science, murraylab.science, smartvillageslab.msd, thirdwavelab.education — all verified present), and 19 single-purpose transaction microsites (see forms-registry finding). No central inventory ties a host to an owner, a retirement date, or a reason it isn't a path on an existing site.",
  "recommendation": "Create an authoritative DNS/subdomain registry (one row per host: business owner, technical owner, CMS, created date, review/retirement date, justification). Make new *.unimelb.edu.au issuance require sign-off against a published test ('why is this not a path under an existing site?'). Default new student-facing content to a PATH on students.unimelb or the faculty site, not a new host. Bulk-import the 415 hosts from cross-site-flow.csv as the seed inventory and assign owners; hosts with no owner after 90 days become retirement candidates. This is the single mechanism that prevents re-fragmentation — every other fix is one-time cleanup without it. Retire the 8 Fine Arts cohort-year subdomains into a single archived path as the proof-of-concept."
