  "title": "Add rel=\"noopener\" and a visible 'opens in new window' cue to external links",
  "evidence": "Of 11,716 target=_blank links I sampled across 9 domains, 8,535 (72.8%) carry no rel=noopener/noreferrer (the's 82.3% was a smaller sample; same order of magnitude). Rate varies by site template: scholarships 98.0%, services 99.6%, fbe 98.4%, arts 98.4%, mdhs 98.5%, alumni 90.7%, students 80.1%, but study 31.2% and law 47.3% are markedly better. Spot-checks show no programmatic 'opens in new window' indication (no aria text, no icon with accessible name). The accessibility issue is the unannounced context change for screen-reader and cognitive users (WCAG 3.2.5); rel=noopener is also a reverse-tabnabbing security/perf hygiene gap. Source: scratchpad/a11y_verify.py target=_blank pass.",
  "recommendation": "At the link-rendering/template level, automatically inject rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" on any anchor with target=_blank, and append a visually-hidden ' (opens in a new window)' span (or an aria-labelled external-link icon) to its accessible name. The ~98%-rate templates (scholarships/services/fbe/arts/mdhs) are the priority; apply as a global template/JS post-process so it covers all 20 domains at once, and add an axe check to flag new target=_blank links without rel."
