  "evidence": "Generic link phrases are low-volume (~0.21% of 39,941 anchors scanned across rendered students.unimelb pages) but present: 'find out more' x26, 'learn more' x24, 'show more' x13, 'read more' x12, 'more information' x8. A meaningful subset are non-functional without JS: 23 instances of generic-text links pointing at href=\"#\" (the cited only 1). Verified example page: students.unimelb.edu.au/support-and-wellbeing/student-services-workshops-and-sessions (note the path is /support-and-wellbeing/..., not the previously-cited /student-support/advice-and-help/...). Out of context these give screen-reader users navigating by link list no destination cue (WCAG 2.4.4). Source: scratchpad/a11y_verify.py generic-link + href='#' pass.",
  "recommendation": "Where 'Show more' toggles content, use a real <button aria-expanded> instead of an <a href=\"#\"> (this fixes all 23 href='#' instances). Where 'Find out more'/'Apply now' is a real link, give it a self-describing label (e.g. 'Find out more about census dates') or at minimum an aria-label. Low volume means this can be a targeted content cleanup on the students/study sites rather than a template change."
